WEBVTT

00:31.677 --> 00:34.886
♪<i> it seems today</i>
<i> that all you see</i> ♪

00:34.972 --> 00:38.098
♪<i> is violence in movies</i>
<i> and sex on tv</i> ♪

00:38.267 --> 00:41.810
♪<i> but where are those</i>
<i> good old-fashioned values</i> ♪

00:41.895 --> 00:44.813
♪<i> on which we used to rely?</i> ♪

00:44.898 --> 00:48.275
♪<i> lucky there's a family guy</i> ♪

00:48.360 --> 00:51.403
♪<i> lucky there's a man who</i>
<i> positively can do</i> ♪

00:51.530 --> 00:53.155
♪<i> all the things that make us</i> ♪

00:53.240 --> 00:54.406
♪<i> laugh and cry</i> ♪

00:54.533 --> 01:00.370
♪<i> he's... A...</i>
<i> Fam... Ily... Guy!</i> ♪

01:06.879 --> 01:07.961
Boy, everybody's here.

01:08.046 --> 01:09.421
Why do you think
we're gathering?

01:09.548 --> 01:12.007
This isn't about the soiled
pants in the toilet, right?

01:12.092 --> 01:13.258
'cause I hadn't heard
about that.

01:13.343 --> 01:14.843
Good morning, employees.

01:14.928 --> 01:16.845
As some of you can tell
by my face,

01:16.930 --> 01:18.263
I have some exciting news.

01:18.348 --> 01:20.974
But first, a pair of husky-size
green pants were found

01:21.059 --> 01:23.435
In the men's room,
positively destroyed.

01:23.562 --> 01:25.145
(whispers): That's what
I hadn't heard about.

01:25.272 --> 01:26.813
Now the exciting news.

01:26.899 --> 01:29.149
The brewery is transitioning
to an open floor plan

01:29.234 --> 01:31.860
And will be called
the pawtucket patriot campus.

01:31.945 --> 01:34.696
To help explain the transition
to our futuristic workplace,

01:34.823 --> 01:36.740
I'd like to share a video
from our investor,

01:36.825 --> 01:39.951
The confusingly charismatic
wework lunatic.

01:40.078 --> 01:42.245
<i> Hey, I'm the guy from wework.</i>

01:42.372 --> 01:44.206
<i> My foremost goal is</i>
<i> to facilitate</i>

01:44.333 --> 01:46.875
<i> An experiential bandwidth</i>
<i> of synergy.</i>

01:46.960 --> 01:48.960
<i> Hammock desks,</i>
<i> scooter desks,</i>

01:49.046 --> 01:51.254
<i>And the world's first desk-desk.</i>

01:51.423 --> 01:54.257
<i> The only desk that</i>
<i> functions as a working desk.</i>

01:54.343 --> 01:57.302
<i>I have been the wework lunatic,</i>
<i> please don't google me.</i>

01:57.387 --> 01:59.638
Our new office will also have

01:59.723 --> 02:01.640
A lady chef
who only makes vegan food,

02:01.725 --> 02:04.142
Pinball machines,
and nursing pods.

02:04.228 --> 02:07.145
Lastly, as we transition
to our new open floor plan,

02:07.231 --> 02:08.521
The brewery will be closed

02:08.649 --> 02:10.273
For the next two months
for construction.

02:10.317 --> 02:11.399
Yes, griffin?

02:11.526 --> 02:15.403
Are the nursing pods,
l-like, for anyone?

02:19.326 --> 02:21.243
If I ordered
a whole cornish game hen,

02:21.328 --> 02:22.369
Would anyone have any?

02:22.454 --> 02:24.287
I'm in for a wing.
What's the occasion?

02:24.414 --> 02:26.248
I just found out
the brewery's closing

02:26.333 --> 02:27.916
So they can turn it into
the kind of workplace

02:28.001 --> 02:29.793
You only see on tv shows.

02:29.920 --> 02:31.544
Work's been crazy for me, too.

02:31.630 --> 02:33.797
We have this case--
guy died on his birthday,

02:33.882 --> 02:35.340
And-- get this--
his family had gotten him

02:35.425 --> 02:36.508
An ice cream cake.

02:36.593 --> 02:38.510
You know, the kind
with ice cream inside

02:38.595 --> 02:39.719
As the cake part?

02:39.846 --> 02:41.513
(laughs)

02:41.598 --> 02:44.182
Wild stuff.
So I'm at the scene...

02:44.268 --> 02:46.142
This story is already
too complicated and boring.

02:46.228 --> 02:47.310
Peter, take over.

02:47.396 --> 02:49.020
My amazon guy
once delivered batteries

02:49.147 --> 02:51.314
-To pat sajak.
-No way!

02:51.358 --> 02:53.566
How did he know there were
batteries in the box?

02:53.735 --> 02:55.068
You know,
whenever they ship a battery,

02:55.195 --> 02:56.987
They got to put that little
warning label on the box?

02:57.114 --> 02:58.571
That's how.

02:58.699 --> 03:00.532
It could've just been something
with a battery in it.

03:00.659 --> 03:02.492
No, he said
he shook it real hard.

03:02.661 --> 03:04.494
I-I think
the focus of this story is

03:04.579 --> 03:06.705
More pat sajak than
the battery part.

03:06.832 --> 03:10.458
Hold on. There's no way
that story was better than mine.

03:12.462 --> 03:14.629
Hey, brian. What's all this?

03:14.715 --> 03:16.381
Oh, just following
in the rich tradition

03:16.466 --> 03:18.008
Of hemingway and faulkner

03:18.126 --> 03:19.718
And putting a little damage
on the old liver.

03:19.845 --> 03:21.136
Another rosé, brian?

03:21.263 --> 03:22.512
Put a spritz on it.

03:22.597 --> 03:26.299
So, is, uh, watching tiktoks
of underage girls

03:26.351 --> 03:28.351
Also part of
your writing process?

03:28.437 --> 03:31.604
The best writing happens when
you're not actually writing.

03:31.732 --> 03:33.648
I just wish
my muse would speak to me.

03:33.734 --> 03:36.484
I'm having a tough time finding
an idea for my next novel.

03:36.653 --> 03:39.988
Well, I'd tell you about
one of my murder cases,

03:40.073 --> 03:42.365
But apparently
I'm a bad storyteller.

03:42.492 --> 03:45.368
-Murder case?
-Oh, yeah, we had one last year.

03:45.495 --> 03:47.662
All signs pointed
to the husband.

03:47.748 --> 03:49.414
-What happened?
-It was the husband.

03:49.499 --> 03:51.958
You know, we have
a whole file of cases in quahog

03:52.044 --> 03:53.960
That would make great stories.

03:54.087 --> 03:56.379
A lot of murdered women
out there, bri.

03:56.465 --> 03:58.590
Half of them named britney,
half of them named lacey.

03:58.675 --> 04:01.134
That's one piece of advice
I always give young parents:

04:01.261 --> 04:02.927
Don't name them
britney or lacey.

04:03.013 --> 04:04.137
Yeah, sad stuff.

04:04.264 --> 04:06.097
You know, true crime is huge
right now.

04:06.183 --> 04:07.599
You could be
sitting on a gold mine.

04:07.642 --> 04:09.059
A gold mine, huh?

04:09.144 --> 04:12.354
And this whole day I thought
it was just a smushed dook.

04:14.941 --> 04:17.150
<i> Announcer (on tv):</i>
<i> We now return to</i>
curb your enthusiasm,

04:17.235 --> 04:20.612
<i> Where jeff garlin just repeats</i>
<i> everything larry says.</i>

04:20.739 --> 04:22.530
<i> So, I put on the shirt.</i>

04:22.699 --> 04:24.449
<i> You put on the shirt!</i>

04:24.576 --> 04:25.867
<i> I paid for it.</i>

04:25.952 --> 04:27.535
<i> You paid for it!</i>

04:27.704 --> 04:29.954
<i> I'm starting to think</i>
<i> you're, uh,</i>

04:30.082 --> 04:31.998
<i> The weakest link in the cast.</i>

04:32.084 --> 04:34.542
<i> Easily the weakest link!</i>

04:34.628 --> 04:37.253
Peter, the bank called
to say we're overdrawn,

04:37.381 --> 04:39.255
And the credit card company
sent us a letter

04:39.383 --> 04:41.508
That just says:
"bitch better have my money."

04:41.593 --> 04:42.759
Visa sent that?

04:42.886 --> 04:44.511
God, they can do
whatever they want in delaware.

04:44.596 --> 04:46.471
Thanks for nothing, sleepy joe.

04:46.598 --> 04:49.265
I wonder if this has anything
to do with me not getting paid

04:49.351 --> 04:50.975
During the brewery renovations.

04:51.103 --> 04:53.311
Wh-what do you mean
"not getting paid"?

04:53.397 --> 04:55.146
Well, preston said
we're all transitioning

04:55.190 --> 04:56.856
To being
independent contractors.

04:56.942 --> 04:58.900
The downside is we're losing
our health insurance,

04:58.985 --> 05:01.861
But there's gonna be a pinball
machine in the break room.

05:01.947 --> 05:03.738
Peter, we can't afford
to go two months

05:03.824 --> 05:05.365
Without your paycheck.

05:05.450 --> 05:07.617
You're gonna have to
find a job in the meantime.

05:07.702 --> 05:10.578
Lois, don't worry.
I got it all figured out.

05:10.705 --> 05:13.164
(shoes tapping)

05:21.800 --> 05:23.925
"dear mr. Griffin,
we regret to inform you

05:24.094 --> 05:26.177
That we cannot offer you
a space."

05:27.264 --> 05:30.432
-(shoes tapping)
-(singsongy): Another big
dance check in the mail.

05:30.517 --> 05:34.269
I was just five years away
from three figures a month.

05:34.396 --> 05:36.563
(shoes tapping slowly)

05:41.945 --> 05:43.069
Joe, this stuff is great.

05:43.196 --> 05:45.363
Yep, one man's murdered,
estranged wife

05:45.449 --> 05:46.948
Is another man's treasure.

05:47.033 --> 05:50.243
Brian, I'm gonna have to ask you
to put down the severed limb.

05:50.370 --> 05:51.828
I brought this from home.

05:51.955 --> 05:53.788
Drop it. Drop it!

05:53.874 --> 05:56.958
Ah, damn it, you said "drop it,"
so now I got to drop it.

05:57.085 --> 05:59.836
You know, we should team up
and write a true crime novel.

05:59.963 --> 06:01.087
You don't happen to have
any cases

06:01.173 --> 06:02.964
Featuring pretty blonde women,
do you?

06:03.133 --> 06:04.507
No, those get solved
pretty quickly.

06:04.634 --> 06:07.719
This victim was brunette
and a little heavy.

06:07.846 --> 06:09.304
Okay, getting warmer.

06:09.389 --> 06:12.140
We'll just change a few
key details so people care.

06:12.225 --> 06:14.142
Gutierrez?
Nope, gordon.

06:14.260 --> 06:16.102
Murdered on
an indian reservation?

06:16.188 --> 06:17.479
Let's try beverly hills.

06:17.647 --> 06:20.315
I'm thinking we go novel,
podcast, docuseries,

06:20.400 --> 06:22.233
Then full-blown blockbuster.

06:22.319 --> 06:25.028
But we'd also be doing this
for the families, right?

06:25.113 --> 06:26.521
Is that a new
streaming platform?

06:26.573 --> 06:28.281
No, like, the families
of the victims?

06:28.366 --> 06:29.532
Oh, right. Yeah, sure.

06:29.743 --> 06:32.118
In fact, we'll give them
a sliver of the proceeds.

06:32.287 --> 06:34.245
And I'll give
the fictional version

06:34.331 --> 06:35.830
Of their daughter bigger boobs.

06:35.957 --> 06:37.499
Like-like real heavy naturals.

06:37.542 --> 06:40.793
Oh, yeah, that sounds
like a good compromise.

06:44.716 --> 06:46.424
Your special cart, mrs. G.

06:46.510 --> 06:49.052
Just gave the wheels
a fresh coat of wd-40.

06:49.137 --> 06:51.429
Why, thank you, james.

06:52.599 --> 06:55.808
Oh, roberto, if you weren't
missing half an arm,

06:55.936 --> 06:57.227
I'd definitely consider it.

06:57.312 --> 06:59.854
Oh, how's the 6029s today, hmm?

06:59.981 --> 07:02.232
Oh, mrs. Lois, very fresh.

07:02.317 --> 07:03.983
What's she talking about, mommy?

07:04.110 --> 07:05.818
(laughs) kale, dear.

07:05.904 --> 07:08.446
It's insider speak for kale.

07:14.162 --> 07:15.954
That can't possibly be a thing.

07:16.039 --> 07:18.581
Let me just find someone
to make sure.

07:21.002 --> 07:24.295
Oh, looks like someone
got pulled from the night shift

07:24.381 --> 07:27.090
'cause I've never seen
this free sample.

07:28.510 --> 07:30.802
-Peter?!
<i> -Man (over speakers):</i>
<i> Ladies and gentlemen,</i>

07:30.929 --> 07:32.679
<i> We have a plot twist</i>
<i> on aisle four.</i>

07:32.847 --> 07:35.348
<i> I'm the assistant manager</i>
<i> who thinks work should be fun,</i>

07:35.433 --> 07:37.475
<i> And definitely not</i>
<i> a corporate spy</i>

07:37.644 --> 07:39.227
<i> Here to keep unions</i>
<i> from forming.</i>

07:39.354 --> 07:41.062
<i> But now that</i>
<i> we're talking about it,</i>

07:41.189 --> 07:42.522
<i> Can you imagine</i>
<i> if you had a grievance</i>

07:42.607 --> 07:44.566
<i> And couldn't talk to me</i>
<i> directly?</i>

07:44.693 --> 07:46.025
<i> Anyway, I'm elliot,</i>

07:46.111 --> 07:47.485
<i> And I'm paying close attention</i>

07:47.571 --> 07:49.821
<i> To who posts what</i>
<i> on the break room cork board.</i>

